<font color="#666666" face="Verdana, Arial, Sans-serif" size="1">WACKY WEB WEEK<br><br></font>


<font face="Arial,Sans-serif" color="black" size="4"><b>

The world's first IT professional</b><br></font>
<font face="Arial,Sans-Serif" color="black" size="1"><br></font>


<table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="white" summary="Wacky Web Week">
<tr>
<td width="110" align="left" valign="top" bgcolor="FFFFFF">
<a href="http://WindowsSecrets.com/links/iqk7giu6euord/7d44c6h/?url=www.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DepJtqYAZCgQ">
<img src="http://WindowsSecrets.com/images/wsn/W070510_IT_Pro.jpg" name="ws_wacky web week"
align="left" width="110" height="100" border="0" hspace="0" vspace="3"
title="First IT pro" alt="First IT pro"></a>
</td>

<td width="510" align="left" valign="top" bgcolor="FFFFFF">

<font face="Arial,Sans-serif" color="black" size="2">

We tend to take our company's helpdesk, IT, and support personnel 
for granted &#8212; until something goes wrong. But do you know how far 
back this venerable profession goes?&nbsp; Have you ever wondered 
how IT pros of ancient days helped employees with the earliest word-processing 
systems?<br><br>

This side-splitting video, recently posted on YouTube, takes a stab at 
answering those questions with a short 
sketch about the first &quot;operating system&quot; &#8212; the book! 

<a href="http://WindowsSecrets.com/links/iqk7giu6euord/7d44c6h/?url=www.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DepJtqYAZCgQ" name="ws_wacky web week">
